05814nam a22008775i 9783110419283DE-B159720200623100627.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200623t20152015gw     fo  d z      eng d  a2015008066  a(OCoLC)945754745  a97831104192837 a10.1515/97831104192832doi  a(DE-B1597)450704  a(OCoLC)932570628  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE00aDS121.65b.E955 2015 7aREL0060902bisacsh00aExile and Return :bThe Babylonian Context /cJonathan Stökl, Caroline Waerzeggers. 1aBerlin ;aBoston : bDe Gruyter, c[2015] 4c©2015  a1 online resource (371 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aBeihefte zur Zeitschrift für die alttestamentliche Wissenschaft ;v47800tFrontmatter -- tTable of Contents -- tIntroduction -- tIdentifying Judeans and Judean Identity in the Babylonian Evidence -- tNegotiating Marriage in Multicultural Babylonia: An Example from the Judean Community in Āl-Yāhūdu -- tFrom Syria to Babylon and Back: The Neirab Archive -- tWest Semitic Groups in the Nippur Region between c. 750 and 330 B.C.E. -- tEgyptians in Babylonia in the Neo-Babylonian and Achaemenid Periods -- tBabylonian Kingship in the Persian Period: Performance and Reception -- t“A Youth Without Blemish, Handsome, Proficient in all Wisdom, Knowledgeable and Intelligent”: Ezekiel’s Access to Babylonian Culture -- tThe Setting of Deutero-Isaiah: Some Linguistic Considerations -- tPicking Up the Pieces of the Little Prince: Refractions of Neo-Babylonian Kingship Ideology in Ezekiel 40–48? -- tThe Reality of the Return: The Biblical Picture Versus Historical Reconstruction -- tSheshbazzar, a Judean or a Babylonian? A Note on his Identity -- tThe Impact of the Second and Third-Generation Returnees as a Model for Understanding the Post-Exilic Context -- tTemple Funding and Priestly Authority in Achaemenid Judah -- tAbbreviations -- tNon-bibliographical abbreviations -- tIndex 0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aMany books of the Hebrew Bible were either composed in some form or edited during the Exilic and post-Exilic periods among a community that was to identify itself as returning from Babylonian captivity. At the same time, a dearth of contemporary written evidence from Judah/Yehud and its environs renders any particular understanding of the process within its social, cultural and political context virtually impossible. This has led some to label the period a dark age or black box – as obscure as it is essential for understanding the history of Judaism. In recent years, however, archaeologists and historians have stepped up their effort to look for and study material remains from the period and integrate the local history of Yehud, the return from Exile, and the restoration of Jerusalem’s temple more firmly within the regional, and indeed global, developments of the time. At the same time, Assyriologists have also been introducing a wide range of cuneiform material that illuminates the economy, literary traditions, practices of literacy and the ideologies of the Babylonian host society – factors that affected those taken into Exile in variable, changing and multiple ways. This volume of essays seeks to exploit these various advances.   aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jun 2020) 0aJewsxHistoryx586 B.C.-70 A.D. 0aJewsxHistoryxBabylonian captivity, 598-515 B.C. 0aJewsxHistoryy586 B.C.-70 A.D. 0aJewsxHistoryyBabylonian captivity, 598-515 B.C. 4aBabylonian Exile. 4aBabylonisches Exil. 4aRemigration. 4aSecond Temple Judaism. 4aZweiter Tempel. 4acultural contact. 4areturn migration. 7aRELIGION / Biblical Criticism & Interpretation / Old Testament.2bisacsh1 aStökl, Jonathan, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aWaerzeggers,